{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16742"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16742"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.17,0.05,0.57,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109752"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4194"},{"type":"tags","id":"4195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4199"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11101"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12962"},{"type":"tags","id":"12963"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109752"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old adolescent presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent because she has not yet had her first menstrual period. She has noticed increased facial and body hair growth over the past two years, as well as deepening of her voice. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her development was normal in early childhood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her height is 165 cm and BMI is 22 kg/m\u00b2. She has Tanner stage five pubic hair, Tanner stage three breast development, facial hirsutism, and clitoromegaly. External genitalia are otherwise normal female type.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone: 4.2 IU/L (1.0-12.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ELuteinizing hormone: 3.8 IU/L (1.0-12.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ETestosterone: 4.2 nmol/L (0.5-2.6)\u003Cbr /\u003E17-hydroxyprogesterone: 42 nmol/L (0.3-4.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPelvic ultrasound shows normal uterus and ovaries\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome","Polycystic ovary syndrome","Turner syndrome","Late-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia","M\u00fcllerian agenesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with primary amenorrhoea and signs of androgen excess (hirsutism, clitoromegaly, voice changes). The markedly elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone level is diagnostic of \u003Cstrong\u003Elate-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E (CAH), specifically 21-hydroxylase deficiency. In late-onset CAH, patients have sufficient enzyme activity to prevent salt-wasting in infancy but develop symptoms of androgen excess in adolescence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present with hirsutism and menstrual irregularities but typically presents with secondary amenorrhoea rather than primary amenorrhoea. While testosterone may be elevated, 17-hydroxyprogesterone would not be as markedly elevated as seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete androgen insensitivity syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with primary amenorrhoea and female external genitalia, but these patients have normal breast development, absent or sparse pubic hair, and high testosterone levels with normal female external genitalia. They would not develop virilisation as their tissues cannot respond to androgens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETurner syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with primary amenorrhoea and short stature, but these patients have elevated gonadotropins (hypergonadotropic hypogonadism) due to primary ovarian dysgenesis and would not show signs of androgen excess. They typically have streak gonads and other characteristic physical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u00fcllerian agenesis\u003C/strong\u003E (Mayer-Rokitansky-K\u00fcster-Hauser syndrome) presents with primary amenorrhoea but normal secondary sexual characteristics. These patients have normal ovarian function and would not show signs of androgen excess. The uterus would be absent on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Late-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia presents with primary amenorrhoea, virilisation, and elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels.","Primary amenorrhoea with virilisation should prompt investigation of androgens and their precursors.","Normal female external genitalia at birth do not exclude congenital adrenal hyperplasia as a cause of primary amenorrhea.","It is important to also consider androgen-secreting tumours with rapidly progressive signs of androgen excess"],"references":["Conway GS. Primary Amenorrhoea [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2017 [cited 2024 Dec 1];19(3). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/3-19/primary-amenorrhoea/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92151"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16742"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92151"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-26T03:55:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-26T03:56:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109752"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations